## Job queue design

For single-user local server, keep it simple:

```typescript
// In-memory job store (lost on restart, acceptable for local use)
const jobs = new Map<string, JobState>();

interface JobState {
  id: string;
  type: 'add' | 'update';
  status: 'pending' | 'running' | 'completed' | 'failed';
  createdAt: number;
  progress?: { current: number; total: number; file?: string };
  result?: SyncResult;
  error?: string;
}

// Background execution
async function runJob(id: string, fn: () => Promise<void>) {
  jobs.get(id)!.status = 'running';
  try {
    await fn();
    jobs.get(id)!.status = 'completed';
  } catch (e) {
    jobs.get(id)!.status = 'failed';
    jobs.get(id)!.error = String(e);
  }
}
```

Progress updates: polling via `GET /api/jobs/:id` (simple, stateless).
WebSocket would be nicer but overkill for v1.

Jobs auto-expire after 1 hour to prevent memory leak.

